The performance of the constructed systems was assayed through the nitrogen photofixation process under visible light illumination (Fig. 4
                     ). The blank test (no catalyst) demonstrates that both light irradiation and photocatalyst are required for e converting nitrogen to ammonia. As Fig. 4 shows, the ammonia production rate is obtained as 400.1 μmol L − 1 g − 1 in the presence of ZnO. The loading of ZnSnO3 on ZnO increases the photoactivity. By increasing the amount of ZnSnO3, the photoactivity rises first and then reduces. The ZnO/ZnSnO3 (30%) sample demonstrates the excellent ammonia production rate 2200 μmol L − 1 g − 1. CDs are a superb co-catalyst in photocatalysis. When CDs have adhered on ZnO/ZnSnO3 (30%) system, the photoactivity is enhanced remarkably. The CDs amount is discovered to be necessary for the advancement effect. The optimal system with 0.5 mL CDs content demonstrates the highest photoactivity. The ammonia generation rate obtains 4600 μmol L − 1 g − 1, which is 11.5 folds premier than ZnO. Also, the effect of light, scavenger, and photocatalyst were investigated and according to these results, the absence of any of these caused a significant reduction in ammonia production. Table 1
                      shows the ammonia production rate over the ZnO/ZnSnO3/CDs (0.5 mL) nanocomposite (this work) and some of the photocatalysts reported in the literature [53–62]. The results in table 1 show that the obtained ternary nanocomposite in present research has higher photocatalytic activity than other photocatalysts. Therefore, it can be concluded that the obtained ZnO/ZnSnO3/CDs photocatalysts could be a promising candidate in feasible usage involving various organic dyes on industrial level.

Herein, a mechanism for the improved photoactivity in the ZnO/ZnSnO3/CDs photocatalysts was proposed according to the above-presented outcomes. Based on the optical gaps, ZnO and ZnSnO3 cannot be excited through visible light excitation. While, when CDs were integrated with the ZnO and ZnSnO3, the enhanced photoability can be attributed to the reasons mentioned below. At first, the addition of CDs into the system increases the light absorption capability owing to their upconversion characteristics. Briefly, due to the up-conversion of long wavelengths to short wavelengths by CDs, the lights with wavelengths larger than 475 nm could be converted to <475 nm by CDs, and leading to exciting the ZnO and ZnSnO3 to produce more charge carriers. We proposed an S-scheme (Step-scheme) heterojunction mechanism for the N2 fixation process on the ZnO/ZnSnO3/CDs nanocomposite (Fig. 8
                     ) [64]. An S-scheme heterojunction is constructed of two componenet with obscure band structures, which is similar to type-II heterojunction but with a completely different charge-transfer way. It is well known that ZnO and ZnSnO3 are n-type semiconductors and their Fermi levels (EF) are located near their CB levels. Moreover, the CB, VB, and EF positions of ZnO are higher than those of the ZnSnO3. Hence, after contacting of these semiconductors, electrons in the ZnO spontaneously flow to ZnSnO3, causing electron accumulation layer and electron depletion layer in the junction region of the ZnSnO3 and ZnO, respectively. The ZnO is positively charged and ZnSnO3 is negatively charged. So, an internal electric field is formed which causes electrons transfer from ZnSnO3 and ZnO. Moreover, when ZnO and ZnSnO3 are in contact, their Fermi level must be balanced at the same level. This causes an upward and downward movement in the Fermi energies of ZnSnO3 and ZnO, respectively. The band bending leads to the recombination of the electrons on the CB of ZnSnO3 with holes on the VB of ZnO at the interface area under the Coulombic attraction between opposite charges. Briefly, the described three factors (the internal electric field, band bending, and Coulombic attraction) operate as the driving forces for the recombination of electrons on the CB of ZnSnO3 with holes on the VB of ZnO [65, 66]. So, the strong photo-induced electrons on the CB of ZnO and the holes on the VB of ZnSnO3 are maintained to participate in photocatalysis process. The electrons in the CB of ZnO with sufficient negative level can convert N2 to NH3 (E°= –0.092 eV) [6], in the presence of generated electrons and H
                     + ions. Moreover, the holes in the VB of ZnSnO3 will oxidize H2O molecules (oxidation potential of water is 1.23 V) [67]. Besides, the CDs acted as a cocatalyst to accept the excited electrons from CB of ZnO. Some electrons collected on the CB of ZnO are inclined to migration to the surface of CDs due to the lower potential of the CDs surface compared to the CB of ZnO. This garlic further assists the migration of electrons from the CB of ZnO, so preventing the delay in continuous excitation of electrons from the VB of ZnO in the S-scheme heterojunction system [68].
